'''Andrew Joseph Reed ''' (born May 10, 1993) is an American [[professional baseball]] [[first baseman]] for the [[Chicago White Sox]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He previously played in MLB for the [[Houston Astros]]. He played [[college baseball]] at [[Kentucky Wildcats baseball|Kentucky]]. He was drafted by the Astros in the second round of the [[2014 Major League Baseball Draft|2014 MLB draft]].

==Early years==
Reed attended [[Terre Haute South Vigo High School]] in [[Terre Haute, Indiana]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribstar.com/collegesports/x360408574/Immense-power-A-leaner-A-J-Reed-making-play-as-elite-prospect|title=Immense power: A leaner A.J. Reed making play as elite prospect|work=Terre Haute Tribune Star|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> During his career he hit .425 with 41 [[home runs]] and 150 [[Run batted in|runs batted in]] (RBI) as a batter and was 26–10 record with a 1.88 [[earned run average]] (ERA), and 390 [[strikeouts]] in 260 innings as a pitcher. Reed was drafted by the [[New York Mets]] in the 25th round of the [[2011 Major League Baseball Draft]], but did not sign and attended the [[University of Kentucky]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribstar.com/sports/x1697313804/Mets-draft-South-s-A-J-Reed|title=New York Mets draft South's A.J. Reed|work=Terre Haute Tribune Star|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref>

==College career==
While at Kentucky he was considered one of the best two-way players in college baseball.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ncaa.com/news/baseball/article/2014-04-12/kentuckys-aj-reed-among-nations-elite-hitter-and-pitcher|title=Kentucky's A.J. Reed among nation's elite as hitter and pitcher|work=NCAA.com|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theneworleansadvocate.com/sports/8883221-171/kentuckys-aj-reed-among-college |title=- Sports - The New Orleans Advocate — New Orleans, Louisiana |work=theneworleansadvocate.com |accessdate=June 30, 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304064748/http://www.theneworleansadvocate.com/sports/8883221-171/kentuckys-aj-reed-among-college |archivedate=March 4, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/kentucky/2014/04/24/kentuckys-reed-nations-top-slugger-mound-ace/8119903/|title=Kentucky's Reed is nation's top slugger — and mound ace|date=April 24, 2014|work=The Courier-Journal|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> As a freshman in [[2012 Kentucky Wildcats baseball team|2012]] at the Kentucky he became the first consensus first-team freshman [[All-American]] in Kentucky's baseball history. He played in 55 games with 51 starts, hitting .300 with four home runs and 43 [[Run batted in|runs batted in]] as a batter. As a pitcher he went 5–3 with a 2.52 ERA and 51 strikeouts over 16 games (five starts). As a sophomore in [[2013 Kentucky Wildcats baseball team|2013]] he started all 55 games and started 14 games as a pitcher. As a batter he hit .280 with 13 home runs and 52 runs batted in. As a pitcher he was 2–8 with a 4.04 ERA and 52 strikeouts.

As a junior in [[2014 Kentucky Wildcats baseball team|2014]], Reed hit .336/.476/.735 and led the nation in home runs with 23. As a pitcher he was 12–2 with a 2.09 ERA and 71 strikeouts. He was the winner of the [[Golden Spikes Award]] and the [[Dick Howser Trophy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/story/_/id/11228384/aj-reed-kentucky-wildcats-winner-golden-spikes-award|title=A.J. Reed of Kentucky Wildcats winner of Golden Spikes Award|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article/mlb/astros-draftee-aj-reed-wins-2014-dick-howser-trophy?ymd=20140614&content_id=79746484&vkey=news_mlb Astros draftee Reed wins Howser Trophy]</ref> He also won numerous other awards, including the [[John Olerud Award]], [[Southeastern Conference Baseball Player of the Year|SEC Player of the Year]], National Player of the Year from [[Collegiate Baseball Newspaper|''Collegiate Baseball'']] and [[American Baseball Coaches Association]], as well as [[Baseball America College Player of the Year Award|Baseball America College Player Of The Year]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/062714aaa.html|title=AJ Reed Wins John Olerud Two-Way Player of the Year Award|work=ukathletics.com|accessdate=June 30, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729231225/http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/062714aaa.html|archive-date=July 29, 2014|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.secdigitalnetwork.com/NEWS/tabid/473/Article/251309/sec-announces-2014-baseball-awards.aspx |title=SEC Announces 2014 Baseball Awards |publisher=Southeastern Conference |date=May 27, 2014 |accessdate=May 28, 2014}}</ref><ref name=CB_NPOY>{{cite press release|title=A.J. Reed Named National Player of the Year|url=http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/052914aab.html|work=May 29, 2014|publisher=[[Kentucky Wildcats|University of Kentucky Athletics]]|accessdate=May 29, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140529214101/http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/052914aab.html|archive-date=May 29, 2014|dead-url=yes|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=BA_CPOY>{{cite press release|title=College Player Of The Year: Kentucky's Reed Starred At Plate, On Mound|url=http://www.baseballamerica.com/college/college-player-of-the-year-kentuckys-reed-starred-at-plate-on-mound/|work=June 11, 2014|publisher=[[Baseball America]]|accessdate=June 11, 2014}}</ref><ref name=UK2014ABCA_NPOY>{{cite web|title=AJ Reed Named ABCA National Player of the Year|url=http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/061814aab.html|publisher=[[University of Kentucky]]|accessdate=June 18, 2014|date=June 18, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140622145245/http://www.ukathletics.com/sports/m-basebl/spec-rel/061814aab.html|archive-date=June 22, 2014|dead-url=yes}}</ref> He was also the SEC Male Athlete of the Year for all sports.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/kentucky/2014/07/01/kentuckys-aj-reed-named-sec-male-athlete-year/11903377/|title=Kentucky's A.J. Reed named SEC Male Athlete of the Year|author=Kyle Tucker, @KyleTucker_CJ|date=July 1, 2014|work=The Courier-Journal|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref>

==Professional career==
===Houston Astros===
Reed was drafted by the [[Houston Astros]] in the second round of the [[2014 Major League Baseball Draft]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://houston.astros.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20140605&content_id=78391930&notebook_id=78395054&vkey=notebook_hou&c_id=hou|title=Astros go for power with Kentucky's Reed in Round 2|work=Houston Astros|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> He signed on June 11.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20140611&content_id=79285898&notebook_id=79297198&vkey=notebook_hou&c_id=hou|title=Astros ink power-hitting 42nd overall pick Reed|work=Houston Astros|accessdate=June 30, 2015}}</ref> Reed hit 34 home runs for the [[Lancaster JetHawks]] of the [[Class A-Advanced]] [[California League]] and [[Corpus Christi Hooks]] of the [[Class AA]] [[Texas League]] in the 2015 season, winning the [[Joe Bauman Home Run Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20150911&content_id=148667888&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_milb&sid=milb|title=Reed wins 2015 Bauman Home Run Award: Second-year Astros pro hit 34 homers to lead Minor League Baseball|work=MiLB.com|date=September 11, 2015|accessdate=September 11, 2015}}</ref>

Reed began the 2016 season with the [[Fresno Grizzlies]] of the [[Class AAA]] [[Pacific Coast League]]. He was called up and made his major league debut on June 25, 2016.<ref>https://www.si.com/mlb/2016/06/24/houston-astros-promote-top-prospect-aj-reed</ref> On July 1, 2016 he recorded his first Major League hit with a single against [[Chicago White Sox]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=360701118|title=Gomez hits 2-run homer to help Astros over White Sox 5-0|date=July 2, 2016|publisher=espn.com|accessdate=July 28, 2016}}</ref> Next day he hit his first Major League home run off Chicago White Sox pitcher [[David Robertson (baseball)|David Robertson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=360702118|title=White Sox's comeback victory over Astros gives Chris Sale MLB-best 14th win|date=July 3, 2016|publisher=espn.com|accessdate=July 28, 2016}}</ref>

On March 21, 2017 he was optioned back to the [[Fresno Grizzlies]] of the [[Class AAA]] [[Pacific Coast League]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://m.astros.mlb.com/roster/transactions/2017/03|title=Transactions|website=Houston Astros|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-03}}</ref> Reed appeared in only 2 games for the Astros in 2017 without recording a stat in 6 at-bats.<ref>{{cite web|last1=McTaggart|first1=Brian|last2=Gurnick|first2=Ken|title=Houston Astros win 2017 World Series|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/260380704/astros-beat-dodgers-to-win-first-world-series/|publisher=MLB|accessdate=November 2, 2017}}</ref> Reed earned his first World Series Championship ring.

On June 28, 2018, Reed was recalled to the Astros when [[Yuli Gurriel]] was on a 3-day [[paternity leave]].  He was optioned back to the Grizzlies on July 3, 2018.  During Reed's [[cup of coffee]], he appeared in one game, with three at bats and no hits. <ref name="milb_stats">{{cite web |title=AJ Reed |url=http://www.milb.com/player/index.jsp?sid=milb&player_id=607223#/career/R/hitting/2018/ALL |website=milb.com |accessdate=August 24, 2018}}</ref>. On July 2, 2019, Reed was designated for assignment by the Astros.<ref>{{cite web|title=Astros designate A.J. Reed for assignment to make room for Jose Urquidy|url=https://www.chron.com/sports/astros/article/Astros-designate-AJ-Reed-assignment-Urquidy-40-man-14067573.php|website=[[The Houston Chronicle]]|author=Chandler Rome|date=July 2, 2019|accessdate=July 2, 2019}}</ref>

On July 2, 2019, Reed was [[designated for assignment]] by the Astros.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rome |first1=Chandler |title=Astros designate A.J. Reed for assignment to make room for Jose Urquidy |url=https://www.chron.com/sports/astros/article/Astros-designate-AJ-Reed-assignment-Urquidy-40-man-14067573.php |accessdate=2 July 2019 |publisher=Houston Chronicle |date=2 July 2019}}</ref>  

===Chicago White Sox===
On July 8, 2019, the [[Chicago White Sox]] claimed Reed off waivers.<ref>{{cite news|author=RotoWire Staff|title=White Sox's AJ Reed: Claimed by White Sox|url=https://www.cbssports.com/fantasy/baseball/news/white-soxs-aj-reed-claimed-by-white-sox/|accessdate=July 8, 2019|publisher=|date=July 8, 2019}}</ref><ref name="CST20190713">{{cite news |last1=Van Schouwen |first1=Daryl |title=Waiver claim AJ Reed embraces fresh start, opportunity with White Sox |url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/white-sox/2019/7/12/20692284/waiver-claim-a-j-reed-joins-white-sox-in-oakland |accessdate=13 July 2019 |publisher=Chicago Sun Times |date=Jul 12, 2019}}</ref>

== Personal life ==
Reed is married to Shelbie Scamihorn, his high school sweetheart.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blog.chron.com/ultimateastros/2015/12/04/after-tying-the-knot-astros-prospect-a-j-reed-back-to-work/|title=After tying the knot, Astros prospect A.J. Reed back to work|last=|first=|last2=|first2=|date=2015-12-04|website=Houston Chronicle|language=en-US|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2019-03-08}}</ref> They have two pet cockatoos, Moose and Buck.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribstar.com/sports/after-another-monster-rbi-season-reed-remains-hopeful-about-big/article_b05139eb-900d-57ad-b7fe-94922fff4a7f.html|title=After another monster RBI season, Reed remains hopeful about big-league opportunity|last=Pearson|first=Craig|date=|website=Terre Haute Tribune-Star|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2019-03-08}}</ref>

